70
00:03:09,142 --> 00:03:10,643
Anything is possible within SimCity

71
00:03:10,643 --> 00:03:14,426
because it is an innately learning-oriented product.

72
00:03:14,426 --> 00:03:15,967
It's the thing that teachers think about when they think

73
00:03:15,967 --> 00:03:16,687
about learning in games.

74
00:03:16,687 --> 00:03:17,327
It'll be perfect.

75
00:03:18,028 --> 00:03:20,949
And so then we put the game in front of kids all by itself

76
00:03:20,949 --> 00:03:22,030
in a school setting.

77
00:03:22,030 --> 00:03:24,311
And they said, well, this is pretty fun,

78
00:03:24,311 --> 00:03:26,412
but we weren't learning anything.

79
00:03:26,412 --> 00:03:27,633
So why are you wasting our time?

80
00:03:27,633 --> 00:03:30,114
And it was really surprising to us

81
00:03:30,114 --> 00:03:32,115
that kids in that particular setting

82
00:03:32,115 --> 00:03:33,156
are hungry for learning.

83
00:03:33,156 --> 00:03:35,117
There was a deep satisfaction and actually

84
00:03:35,117 --> 00:03:37,198
a deep affective state that they went

85
00:03:37,198 --> 00:03:38,859
into when they were learning that was not

86
00:03:38,859 --> 00:03:40,900
what we were used to seeing from when they were playing games

87
00:03:40,900 --> 00:03:42,361
and when they were having fun.

88
00:03:43,918 --> 00:03:46,941
And so I realized fun is learning is the beginning.

89
00:03:46,941 --> 00:03:47,881
It's not the end.

90
00:03:47,881 --> 00:03:49,903
And there is so much more that we

91
00:03:49,903 --> 00:03:52,204
have to learn about the learning process

92
00:03:52,204 --> 00:03:54,826
and how it applies to fun, how it is distinctive emotionally

93
00:03:54,826 --> 00:03:55,827
from fun.

94
00:03:55,827 --> 00:03:58,128
And this affective state that kids went into

95
00:03:58,128 --> 00:04:00,690
was incredibly fascinating to me.

96
00:04:00,690 --> 00:04:01,691
I couldn't place it.

97
00:04:01,691 --> 00:04:03,192
It was actually kind of a new state.

98
00:04:03,952 --> 00:04:06,495
And you need really good teachers to create it,

99
00:04:06,495 --> 00:04:08,217
or really good products to create it.

100
00:04:08,217 --> 00:04:10,500
And I was talking to one of our learning designers

101
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:13,203
about how you might look at that affective state.

102
00:04:13,203 --> 00:04:15,546
And I said, you know, has anybody ever tried

103
00:04:15,546 --> 00:04:18,449
to identify a palette of universal emotions?

104
00:04:19,052 --> 00:04:19,893
And he said, yeah.

105
00:04:19,893 --> 00:04:22,134
There's a guy named Paul Ekman, who

106
00:04:22,134 --> 00:04:24,155
did a study, probably one of the studies

107
00:04:24,155 --> 00:04:25,356
that he's most well-known for.

108
00:04:25,356 --> 00:04:28,037
He's actually the basis for the show Lie to Me,

109
00:04:28,037 --> 00:04:31,179
where he was connecting emotional states

110
00:04:31,179 --> 00:04:32,560
to facial expressions.

111
00:04:32,560 --> 00:04:34,581
And he took a whole bunch of photographs

112
00:04:34,581 --> 00:04:37,603
all over the world of people having different emotions

113
00:04:37,603 --> 00:04:39,804
and asked people in all different countries

114
00:04:39,804 --> 00:04:40,945
to identify what was going on.

115
00:04:41,045 --> 00:04:43,227
And then they dropped all of this all the way down

116
00:04:43,227 --> 00:04:45,269
and found seven universal emotions.

117
00:04:45,269 --> 00:04:47,451
It was six initially, and then a seventh one was added.

118
00:04:47,451 --> 00:04:51,715
So there's disgust, contempt, sadness, happiness, fear,

119
00:04:51,715 --> 00:04:54,358
anger, and surprise, universal across all cultures

120
00:04:54,358 --> 00:04:55,058
and all people.

121
00:04:55,878 --> 00:04:56,478
But where's fun?

122
00:04:56,478 --> 00:04:59,339
None of these seemed individually to be fun.

123
00:04:59,339 --> 00:05:01,420
Some of them were sort of related,

124
00:05:01,420 --> 00:05:04,360
like definitely sadness sometimes.

125
00:05:04,360 --> 00:05:05,921
Like if you played Final Fantasy VII,

126
00:05:05,921 --> 00:05:08,442
you would experience this terrible sadness.

127
00:05:08,442 --> 00:05:10,742
Happiness seemed to be pretty close.

128
00:05:10,742 --> 00:05:12,323
Surprise seemed really important,

129
00:05:12,323 --> 00:05:14,304
but none of them individually seemed

130
00:05:14,304 --> 00:05:15,764
to be hitting this thing that was fun.

131
00:05:17,410 --> 00:05:22,015
And eventually what I realized was that fun wasn't one emotion.

132
00:05:22,015 --> 00:05:24,157
It was a process between multiple emotions.

133
00:05:24,157 --> 00:05:26,199
It was something that was arrived on,

134
00:05:26,199 --> 00:05:28,541
or an affective state that was emergent out

135
00:05:28,541 --> 00:05:31,303
of multiple emotions that actually

136
00:05:31,303 --> 00:05:32,645
seemed to have a consistent sequence.

137
00:05:32,645 --> 00:05:34,326
And that seemed really interesting.

138
00:05:34,326 --> 00:05:35,107
So here comes the word.

139
00:05:38,210 --> 00:05:42,392
I call it SOFIA, the Game Learn Emotion.

140
00:05:42,392 --> 00:05:45,815
And I think it's the cognitive process by which we convert

141
00:05:45,815 --> 00:05:47,696
fear into happiness through surprise.

142
00:05:47,696 --> 00:05:50,638
So you can look at it as this transitional state where

143
00:05:50,638 --> 00:05:53,780
initially you're fearful, and then you have this moment

144
00:05:53,780 --> 00:05:56,261
of realization and delight, and then you feel super happy.

145
00:05:56,261 --> 00:05:59,103
And this process actually deeply does

146
00:05:59,103 --> 00:06:02,345
connect with a lot of the stuff that Lev Vygotsky said

147
00:06:02,345 --> 00:06:05,427
and Piaget has said about what happens when kids play.

