00:08:21,420 --> 00:08:22,581
And I think these are the games that we

223
00:08:22,581 --> 00:08:26,303
tend to think about as either smart fun or learning fun games.

224
00:08:26,303 --> 00:08:28,845
And if we kind of put them all together and look at them,

225
00:08:28,845 --> 00:08:30,946
I think partly what we see is that they

226
00:08:30,946 --> 00:08:32,467
have some sort of connection to the real world.

227
00:08:32,467 --> 00:08:34,889
There's some kind of exploration that's going on

228
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:36,130
and some kind of discovery.

229
00:08:36,130 --> 00:08:37,731
And you're creating order out of chaos.

230
00:08:37,731 --> 00:08:39,692
And then when you have that ordered state

231
00:08:39,692 --> 00:08:41,373
that you've created in the world,

232
00:08:41,373 --> 00:08:43,294
you have this deep satisfaction about yourself.

233
00:08:43,294 --> 00:08:44,315
You feel mastery.

234
00:08:44,315 --> 00:08:45,296
You feel understanding.

235
00:08:45,596 --> 00:08:48,221
you feel actually like you have a bit more of a grip on your life.

236
00:08:48,221 --> 00:08:51,306
And by the way, these feelings might

237
00:08:51,306 --> 00:08:53,309
be missing from formal education today,

238
00:08:53,309 --> 00:08:56,094
which might be part of why there's so much effort

239
00:08:56,094 --> 00:08:57,356
to bring games into education.

