00:09:47,777 --> 00:09:50,118
And if some games have more Sophia than others,

265
00:09:50,118 --> 00:09:52,178
it got me thinking about how can we actually

266
00:09:52,178 --> 00:09:54,019
categorize games differently than just

267
00:09:54,019 --> 00:09:54,979
according to their mechanics.

268
00:09:54,979 --> 00:09:57,460
I think that if you look at games

269
00:09:57,460 --> 00:09:59,720
as a comparison between the core emotion

270
00:09:59,720 --> 00:10:01,661
that the game itself is evoking, you

271
00:10:01,661 --> 00:10:03,681
start to get a really interesting hierarchy.

272
00:10:03,681 --> 00:10:06,102
And I would like to see the rest of this built out.

273
00:10:06,102 --> 00:10:08,643
There's the fear genre of Silent Hill.

274
00:10:09,063 --> 00:10:11,925
and amnesia that just makes you feel afraid in so many ways

275
00:10:11,925 --> 00:10:14,867
and has you confront all of these horror concepts.

276
00:10:14,867 --> 00:10:16,788
There's the together genre, which

277
00:10:16,788 --> 00:10:18,869
you can see this kind of esoteric collection of games

278
00:10:18,869 --> 00:10:21,391
that really evoke this emotion of togetherness

279
00:10:21,391 --> 00:10:24,713
and knowing other people and knowing how human beings work.

280
00:10:24,713 --> 00:10:27,134
And then there's, I think, a relatively new,

281
00:10:27,134 --> 00:10:29,076
or there's some old games, but these games

282
00:10:29,076 --> 00:10:31,557
are becoming bigger, the complicity genre with Papers,

283
00:10:31,557 --> 00:10:33,498
Please and Sweatshop in it, which

284
00:10:33,498 --> 00:10:35,660
is my favorite new genre that actually

285
00:10:35,660 --> 00:10:37,201
has this very complex emotion of.

286
00:10:37,781 --> 00:10:42,684
initial engagement, and then mastery over a system,

287
00:10:42,684 --> 00:10:46,447
and then, shit, what have I done?

288
00:10:46,447 --> 00:10:48,929
This is a very complex emotion, really fascinating.

289
00:10:48,929 --> 00:10:51,911
But within all of those genres, because Sophia

290
00:10:51,911 --> 00:10:54,232
is the game emotion, there's Sophia in all of them.

291
00:10:54,232 --> 00:10:57,334
So you can take two games, like God of War and Animal Crossing.

292
00:10:57,334 --> 00:10:59,836
In God of War, you're going to discover controls.

293
00:10:59,836 --> 00:11:01,837
It has this really elegant tutorial system

294
00:11:01,837 --> 00:11:04,739
that leads you to think that you are achieving your own mastery

295
00:11:04,739 --> 00:11:05,800
over these controls.

296
00:11:05,980 --> 00:11:08,481
that are eventually going to make you feel extremely powerful

297
00:11:08,481 --> 00:11:09,761
once you have them.

298
00:11:09,761 --> 00:11:13,503
In Animal Crossing, even though it's a completely open sandbox

299
00:11:13,503 --> 00:11:16,323
game with all of the emergent narrative very whimsical,

300
00:11:16,323 --> 00:11:18,684
it has this fish loop in it and many other loops,

301
00:11:18,684 --> 00:11:20,885
such as digging up fossils, that give you

302
00:11:20,885 --> 00:11:23,526
a mastery sense that make you feel very grounded and mastered

303
00:11:23,526 --> 00:11:24,466
in that world.

304
00:11:24,706 --> 00:11:30,467
So, and I think in both of these games, you're still finding the fear in God of War getting

305
00:11:30,467 --> 00:11:31,547
destroyed.

306
00:11:31,547 --> 00:11:37,548
And then you're getting surprised and delighted, and eventually you're reaching happiness because

307
00:11:37,548 --> 00:11:38,289
you have this feeling of mastery.

308
00:11:38,289 --> 00:11:42,409
So Sophia is the process, and it drives the core.

309
00:11:42,409 --> 00:11:45,810
The feelings of mastery in God of War create fear.

310
00:11:45,810 --> 00:11:47,490
They create dominance.

311
00:11:47,490 --> 00:11:52,131
Feelings of mastery in Animal Crossing create a sense of togetherness, a feeling of understanding

312
00:11:52,131 --> 00:11:53,832
people and being connected to them.

313
00:11:56,378 --> 00:11:57,720
Oops, so when we follow this down,

314
00:11:57,720 --> 00:11:58,961
I just gave that away completely.

315
00:11:58,961 --> 00:11:59,541
That sucked.

316
00:11:59,541 --> 00:12:01,523
OK, I was going to see if you could

317
00:12:01,523 --> 00:12:05,767
identify these games based on their loops themselves.

318
00:12:05,767 --> 00:12:08,910
Let's take, I guess, the one on it's my left.

319
00:12:08,910 --> 00:12:10,931
I'm not sure if it's your left.

320
00:12:10,931 --> 00:12:12,353
Aim, shoot, and watch.

321
00:12:12,353 --> 00:12:15,195
Anybody who did not see the slide want to guess.

322
00:12:17,557 --> 00:12:18,698
No, it's too much anyway.

323
00:12:18,698 --> 00:12:22,501
So these two loops, I think, are very interesting

324
00:12:22,501 --> 00:12:24,402
because you can take the individual mechanics that

325
00:12:24,402 --> 00:12:27,124
form their core loop and bring them back together

326
00:12:27,124 --> 00:12:30,087
to create a core emotion.

327
00:12:30,087 --> 00:12:32,749
Now, in the case of Angry Birds on the left,

328
00:12:32,749 --> 00:12:35,331
the dissonance between these core mechanics

329
00:12:35,331 --> 00:12:37,973
creates this wackiness in combination

330
00:12:37,973 --> 00:12:41,096
with destruction that gives the game an extremely unique feel.

331
00:12:41,576 --> 00:12:43,497
However, the World of Warcraft loop

332
00:12:43,497 --> 00:12:46,219
creates something that's this fantasy adventure power feeling

333
00:12:46,219 --> 00:12:48,540
that's a very widely and deeply explored

334
00:12:48,540 --> 00:12:49,501
genre in games in general.

335
00:12:49,501 --> 00:12:51,302
So you could apply the World of Warcraft loop

336
00:12:51,302 --> 00:12:53,023
to all kinds of different games.

337
00:12:53,023 --> 00:12:55,124
What unifies them is their core emotion.

338
00:12:55,124 --> 00:12:57,165
But that core emotion emerges from

339
00:12:57,165 --> 00:12:58,606
the individual mechanical connections

340
00:12:58,606 --> 00:13:00,647
between the verbs that form the heart of the game.

341
00:13:04,765 --> 00:13:06,467
So when we're making learning games,

342
00:13:06,467 --> 00:13:10,991
and I think it's very integral to why all of these thoughts

343
00:13:10,991 --> 00:13:12,993
emerge from the process of making learning games,

344
00:13:12,993 --> 00:13:14,434
we have an effect we want to achieve,

345
00:13:14,434 --> 00:13:15,715
which is that the player at the end

346
00:13:15,715 --> 00:13:17,737
should actually be able to perform something

347
00:13:17,737 --> 00:13:19,679
that prior to playing the game they could not perform.

348
00:13:19,679 --> 00:13:20,500
It's very specific.

349
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:23,122
But it is not effective.

350
00:13:23,122 --> 00:13:25,564
Mostly, it's not emotional, not unless you force it to be.

351
00:13:26,085 --> 00:13:29,728
So, when we thought about how could we make this into an actual great game,

352
00:13:29,728 --> 00:13:31,970
instead of something that's just very performance-based,

353
00:13:31,970 --> 00:13:35,112
and a lot of the sort of educational games that we think of as not being...

354
00:13:35,112 --> 00:13:38,716
When we say they're not games, there's a lot of things that we're saying,

355
00:13:38,716 --> 00:13:40,997
but partly I think what we're saying is that they're not very emotional,

356
00:13:40,997 --> 00:13:42,639
and they're not creating an emotional effect.

357
00:13:42,639 --> 00:13:44,440
So when we thought about argumentation...

358
00:13:45,161 --> 00:13:48,102
we thought about what progression of emotions

359
00:13:48,102 --> 00:13:50,023
do we want to have that would make you feel

360
00:13:50,023 --> 00:13:51,984
as though you had mastery over this competency.

361
00:13:51,984 --> 00:13:54,606
It's a little bit tricky because there's a lot we have to do

362
00:13:54,606 --> 00:13:56,747
to achieve the actual effect of increasing

363
00:13:56,747 --> 00:13:58,368
your argumentation competency,

364
00:13:58,368 --> 00:14:00,109
but I think there's an emotional progression

365
00:14:00,109 --> 00:14:02,450
we have to take the player through too if we're doing well,

366
00:14:02,450 --> 00:14:05,071
which is to say, here's the feeling of mastery

367
00:14:05,071 --> 00:14:06,372
over this particular competency

368
00:14:06,372 --> 00:14:08,593
that's really more in a guitar hero space.

369
00:14:08,593 --> 00:14:11,094
Guitar hero is not gonna make you better at playing guitar,

370
00:14:11,094 --> 00:14:13,055
but you will feel like you're better at playing guitar.

371
00:14:13,616 --> 00:14:15,104
And that's very motivating, right?

372
00:14:15,104 --> 00:14:17,114
It makes you think, I want that thing.

373
00:14:18,584 --> 00:14:21,485
And emotions, it turns out, can be pretty complicated.

374
00:14:21,485 --> 00:14:24,087
I think our approach in what we're

375
00:14:24,087 --> 00:14:26,368
trying to do with these games is actually ultimately

376
00:14:26,368 --> 00:14:27,508
to alleviate suffering.

377
00:14:27,508 --> 00:14:30,370
If you look at Sophia Loop, that fear

378
00:14:30,370 --> 00:14:32,290
is already existing inside of a person.

379
00:14:32,290 --> 00:14:33,911
They just kind of don't know that it's there.

380
00:14:33,911 --> 00:14:36,192
If you have an absence in your world model,

381
00:14:36,192 --> 00:14:39,354
you actually are going to be feeling

382
00:14:39,354 --> 00:14:41,215
bad things about that absence.

383
00:14:41,215 --> 00:14:43,015
If we can identify what that is, then we

384
00:14:43,015 --> 00:14:44,976
can create a context by which we can tell a player,

385
00:14:44,976 --> 00:14:46,337
here's why you want to do this thing.

386
00:14:46,857 --> 00:14:49,859
For the most part, in games that are pure entertainment games,

387
00:14:49,859 --> 00:14:52,441
we don't have to say why you should do something.

388
00:14:52,441 --> 00:14:54,762
I don't need a why for why I'm going to kill the dragon.

389
00:14:54,762 --> 00:14:57,084
I'm going to kill the dragon because the dragon is there.

390
00:14:57,084 --> 00:14:58,645
And that's a lot harder when you're

391
00:14:58,645 --> 00:15:01,767
talking about Pascal's triangle or the quadratic equation.

392
00:15:01,767 --> 00:15:05,709
And the thing is, what if Pascal's triangle is actually

393
00:15:05,709 --> 00:15:07,510
way more important than killing the dragon?

394
00:15:07,510 --> 00:15:08,211
You have a problem.

395
00:15:08,211 --> 00:15:09,591
You have to actually articulate the why.

396
00:15:09,591 --> 00:15:13,794
So the why for us with argumentation was,

397
00:15:14,832 --> 00:15:17,592
If you don't have argumentation, you're a little bit helpless

398
00:15:17,592 --> 00:15:18,772
in the world of people.

399
00:15:18,772 --> 00:15:20,013
You're socially not effective.

400
00:15:20,013 --> 00:15:22,893
You can't persuade people that what you think is important.

401
00:15:22,893 --> 00:15:23,994
You're confused.

402
00:15:23,994 --> 00:15:27,154
You can't articulate the things that are important to you.

403
00:15:27,154 --> 00:15:29,275
So if we could reverse this and address

404
00:15:29,275 --> 00:15:31,115
the pain of absence of argumentation,

405
00:15:31,115 --> 00:15:34,396
we would create something that makes clarity and structure,

406
00:15:34,396 --> 00:15:36,977
wittiness, and that you have this compelling effect

407
00:15:36,977 --> 00:15:38,937
on the people around you because you're so persuasive

408
00:15:38,937 --> 00:15:41,678
and that persuasion is grounded in reason and logic.

409
00:15:45,415 --> 00:15:49,778
So the theory of this is nice, but what do we do with it?

410
00:15:49,778 --> 00:15:53,720
I think that Sophia is a lens through which

411
00:15:53,720 --> 00:15:55,000
we can view games.

412
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:58,883
I think that we can identify lots of problems

413
00:15:58,883 --> 00:16:01,244
that emerge from the absence of this process

414
00:16:01,244 --> 00:16:02,625
being clearly articulated.

415
00:16:02,625 --> 00:16:05,466
This is sort of adjacent to ideas about

416
00:16:05,466 --> 00:16:08,488
ludonarrative dissonance, if the performance of something

417
00:16:08,488 --> 00:16:13,450
is different than the narrative that is given to the player.

418
00:16:13,983 --> 00:16:17,725
It's more abstract to say, what if your core emotion is either

419
00:16:17,725 --> 00:16:21,186
not what you intend it to be or is out of alignment

420
00:16:21,186 --> 00:16:22,027
with itself?

421
00:16:22,027 --> 00:16:24,228
What if the core verbs that you're asking a player

422
00:16:24,228 --> 00:16:27,370
to perform over and over don't create the emotion

423
00:16:27,370 --> 00:16:30,591
that you hope that you want players to achieve?

424
00:16:30,591 --> 00:16:33,073
I've seen a lot of games and a lot of processes of games

425
00:16:33,073 --> 00:16:35,734
where we don't even really think about how do we want

426
00:16:35,734 --> 00:16:36,914
the player to feel at the end.

427
00:16:36,914 --> 00:16:40,856
Or how we want the player to feel at the end

428
00:16:40,856 --> 00:16:40,957
is.

429
00:16:42,030 --> 00:16:45,072
good, or having fun, or engaged,

430
00:16:45,072 --> 00:16:46,133
and not something very precise,

431
00:16:46,133 --> 00:16:49,375
which has to do with the absence of the game

432
00:16:49,375 --> 00:16:52,518
before the presence of it and how it changes you.

433
00:16:52,518 --> 00:16:54,900
I think a lot of times there can be not enough surprise

434
00:16:54,900 --> 00:16:55,740
preceding satisfaction.

435
00:16:55,740 --> 00:16:59,443
This is a particular problem inside of educational games

436
00:16:59,443 --> 00:17:01,405
where you can guide a player through something,

437
00:17:01,405 --> 00:17:03,386
actually it's in social games too,

438
00:17:03,386 --> 00:17:06,609
but if you don't allow them to discover for themselves

439
00:17:06,609 --> 00:17:08,050
what is supposed to happen next,

440
00:17:08,050 --> 00:17:09,611
the experience feels very flat.

441
00:17:10,652 --> 00:17:15,136
If you don't clearly illuminate the fear and the why,

442
00:17:15,136 --> 00:17:17,658
you can also have a lack of tension in the game,

443
00:17:17,658 --> 00:17:20,781
a lack of reason to play that ultimately manifests

444
00:17:20,781 --> 00:17:22,362
as lost retention.

445
00:17:22,362 --> 00:17:25,244
And by the way, all of these things together

446
00:17:25,244 --> 00:17:26,606
are the same problems you would have

447
00:17:26,606 --> 00:17:28,407
if you were trying to teach someone something.

